rn religions?</span><hr size=1> DS,<br>
 You might enjoy looking into a comparative religions course. I doubt it is offered in high school but if you are up to it, you may be able to audit a college course. Perhaps during a summer session.<br>
In my layman's view, Taoism, Buddhism, et al are mostly about an afterlife and religious path. They dwell a lot on heaven, heavens, there being more to life than we see, hear or feel with our physical bodies. They are religions and I tend not to lean toward that end of the spiritual spectrum to attain fulfillment or a higher &quot;goal&quot; in some beyond. I do think they can carry a lot of meaningful insight to how I live in the here and now... in the present. So, there is a lot of practical use, a more tangible philosophy. Does that make sense? Prob'ly not.<br>
Regarding Taoism, read the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">Tao Te Ching</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> by Lao Tzu. You can glean a lot from it, depending on how introspective you tend to be, I guess.<br>
Here is the entire Chapter 7 (thus easy, quick read <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    )<br>
<br>
&quot;Heaven and earth last forever.<br>
Why do heaven and earth last forever?<br>
They are unborn, <br>
So ever living.<br>
The sage stays behind, thus he is ahead.<br>
He is detached, thus at one with all.<br>
Through selfless action, he attains fulfillment.&quot;<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>My</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> inversion: (written for an essay way back in 1996 <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    )<br>
<br>
&quot;Heaven and earth do not last forever.<br>
Why don't heaven and earth last forever?<br>
They were born and so they will die.<br>
The sage stays behind, thus he is not ahead.<br>
He is detached, thus at one with none.<br>
Through selfish action, he attains his own fulfillment.&quot;<br>
<br>
It could be said that selfishness will lead to destruction of all that we are surrounded by. We must be careful not to take advantage. What we can do is give of ourselves without ignoring ourselves. Otherwise, how can we maintain all that without maintaining ourselves, physically and mentally? Balance is essential. That is what speaks to me. <br>
